&lt;h2 class="relative group">What are different containers in HTML?
&lt;div id="what-are-different-containers-in-html" class="anchor">&lt;/div>
&lt;span
class="absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 ltr:-left-6 rtl:-right-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100">
&lt;a class="group-hover:text-primary-300 dark:group-hover:text-neutral-700"
style="text-decoration-line: none !important;" href="#what-are-different-containers-in-html" aria-label="Anchor">#&lt;/a>
&lt;/span>
&lt;/h2>
&lt;p>In HTML and CSS, a &lt;strong>&amp;ldquo;container&amp;rdquo; tag&lt;/strong> isn’t a special keyword — it’s a &lt;strong>general term&lt;/strong> used to describe any element that wraps or groups other elements. They don&amp;rsquo;t of any size of their own, but the size of all the elements put inside the container is their size.&lt;/p></description></item></channel></rss>